paragraphs.text:
%md
## Auto Insurance Claims Fraud - Supervised Learning

#### Nearly one of 10 Americans would commit insurance fraud if they knew they could get away with it. Nearly one of four Americans say it’s ok to defraud insurers.   About one in 10 people agree it’s ok to submit claims for items that aren’t lost or damaged, or for personal injuries that didn’t occur. Two of five people are “not very likely” or “not likely at all” to report someone who ripped of an insurer.  Accenture Ltd.(2003)   Nearly three of 10 Americans (29 percent) wouldn't report insurance scams committed by someone they know.  Progressive Insurance (2001)


#### This notebook shows how to "flag" anomalous insurance claims using an unsupervised learning algorithm (1-Class Support Vector Machine).  The notebook first builds a 1-Class SVM model and then applies the model to flag unusual or suspicious auto insurance claims .   The anomaly detection model can also be applied to “score” new records.  The entire machine learning methodology runs inside the ADW.

####  Created by and Last Updated October 2020 by Charlie Berger and Dohoon Kim

msg.data:
Auto Insurance Claims Fraud - Supervised Learning

Nearly one of 10 Americans would commit insurance fraud if they knew they could get away with it. Nearly one of four Americans say it’s ok to defraud insurers. About one in 10 people agree it’s ok to submit claims for items that aren’t lost or damaged, or for personal injuries that didn’t occur. Two of five people are “not very likely” or “not likely at all” to report someone who ripped of an insurer. Accenture Ltd.(2003) Nearly three of 10 Americans (29 percent) wouldn't report insurance scams committed by someone they know. Progressive Insurance (2001)

This notebook shows how to “flag” anomalous insurance claims using an unsupervised learning algorithm (1-Class Support Vector Machine). The notebook first builds a 1-Class SVM model and then applies the model to flag unusual or suspicious auto insurance claims . The anomaly detection model can also be applied to “score” new records. The entire machine learning methodology runs inside the ADW.

Created by and Last Updated October 2020 by Charlie Berger and Dohoon Kim

%md

## Business Problem

#### Based on "labeled data" derived from automobile insurance claims evaluators (see related Auto Insurance Claims Fraud - Unsupervised Learning OML Notebook), we can now build supervised learning models that better target known insurance claims fraud.   Based on this historical "labeled data" (Fraudfound Yes/No), we would like to build predictive models to detect likely fraudulent auto claims.

paragraphs.title: Display Suspicious Auto Claims in Descending Order
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMS_CLASS_MODEL_GLM, 'Yes' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS
))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Display Suspicious Claims by AGE of PolicyHolder
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMS_CLASS_MODEL_GLM, '0' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS
))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.text:

SELECT * FROM

paragraphs.title: Show the Top 5 Most Suspicious Customers
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
(select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, NUMBEROFCARS, WITNESSPRESENT, prediction_probability(CLAIMS_CLASS_MODEL_GLM, 'Yes' using *) prob_fraud
from CLAIMS
))
where rnk <= 5
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: Create table CLAIMS_SUSPICIOUS for investigation using APEX or Oracle Analytics Cloud
paragraphs.text:
%sql

CREATE TABLE CLAIMS_SUSPICIOUS AS 
  SELECT * FROM
  (select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, round(prob_fraud*100,2) percent_fraud,
      rank() over (order by prob_fraud desc) rnk from
  (select POLICYNUMBER, AGEOFPOLICYHOLDER, SEX, MARITALSTATUS, prediction_probability(CLAIMS_CLASS_MODEL_GLM, 'Yes' using *) prob_fraud
   from CLAIMS
  ))
order by percent_fraud desc;

paragraphs.title: View table CLAIMS_SUSPICIOUS
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT * FROM CLAIMS_SUSPICIOUS;
